1
00:00:51,960 --> 00:00:54,394
<i>(Bond)</i> Where is he?

2
00:00:54,480 --> 00:00:57,472
I shan't ask you politely next time.

3
00:01:00,800 --> 00:01:04,236
- Where is Blofeld?
- Cai... Cai...

4
00:01:04,320 --> 00:01:05,673
Cairo.

5
00:01:08,960 --> 00:01:11,349
Cards.

6
00:01:12,200 --> 00:01:14,839
Hit me.

7
00:01:17,680 --> 00:01:21,070
<i>(Bond)</i> One chance. Where can I find him?

8
00:01:21,160 --> 00:01:24,550
Marie... Ask Marie.

9
00:01:24,640 --> 00:01:27,438
Who are you?

10
00:01:27,520 --> 00:01:30,512
My name is Bond... James Bond.

11
00:01:30,600 --> 00:01:32,955
Is there something I can do for you?

12
00:01:33,040 --> 00:01:36,794
Yes, as a matter of fact, there is.

13
00:01:36,880 --> 00:01:41,237
There is something I'd like you
to get off your chest.

14
00:01:41,320 --> 00:01:43,151
<i>(Marie gasps)</i>

15
00:01:43,240 --> 00:01:45,834
Where is Ernst Stavro Blofeld?

16
00:01:47,080 --> 00:01:48,991
Speak up, darling. I can't hear you.

17
00:01:49,960 --> 00:01:53,270
<i>(man)</i> We now come
to phase four: The nose.

18
00:01:53,360 --> 00:01:57,558
In my opinion, the most difficult part
of a plastic transformation.

19
00:01:57,640 --> 00:02:01,553
I want the operation done tonight.
There's no time left.

20
00:02:01,640 --> 00:02:04,916
But, señor Blofeld, this is
a most delicate procedure.

21
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:07,116
Tonight.

22
00:02:17,640 --> 00:02:21,428
Keep the temperature
at precisely 80 degrees.

23
00:03:27,720 --> 00:03:30,109
<i>(Blofeld)</i> Making mud pies, 007?

24
00:03:34,800 --> 00:03:39,794
He would have been me in a few days,
if you'd given the poor fellow a chance.

25
00:03:39,880 --> 00:03:43,509
Such a pity. I was dying to see
how the operation turned out.

26
00:03:44,280 --> 00:03:46,589
Get his gun.

27
00:03:46,680 --> 00:03:48,716
Hold it! Get your hands up.

28
00:04:02,480 --> 00:04:05,119
Kill him!

29
00:04:34,440 --> 00:04:37,637
Welcome to hell, Blofeld.

30
00:04:39,200 --> 00:04:41,714
<i>(cat shrieks)</i>

31
00:04:43,720 --> 00:04:46,280
<i>(~ "Diamonds Are Forever"</i>
<i>by Shirley Bassey)</i>

32
00:05:02,800 --> 00:05:06,839
<i>~ Diamonds are forever</i>

33
00:05:06,920 --> 00:05:11,391
<i>~ They are all I need to please me</i>

34
00:05:11,480 --> 00:05:16,076
<i>~ They can stimulate and tease me</i>

35
00:05:16,160 --> 00:05:18,754
<i>~ They won't leave in the night</i>

36
00:05:18,840 --> 00:05:24,233
<i>~ I've no fear that they might desert me</i>

37
00:05:26,360 --> 00:05:29,591
<i>~ Diamonds are forever</i>

38
00:05:30,640 --> 00:05:35,236
<i>~ Hold one up and then caress it</i>

39
00:05:35,320 --> 00:05:40,110
<i>~ Touch it, stroke it and undress it</i>

40
00:05:40,200 --> 00:05:42,475
<i>~ I can see every part</i>

41
00:05:42,560 --> 00:05:48,954
<i>~ Nothing hides in the heart to hurt me</i>

42
00:05:49,040 --> 00:05:53,795
<i>~ I don't need love</i>

43
00:05:53,880 --> 00:05:57,270
<i>~ For what good will love do me?</i>

44
00:05:58,280 --> 00:06:02,319
<i>~ Diamonds never lie to me</i>

45
00:06:03,320 --> 00:06:08,872
<i>~ For when love's gone</i>

46
00:06:08,960 --> 00:06:12,839
<i>~ They'll lustre on</i>

47
00:06:14,800 --> 00:06:18,475
<i>~ Diamonds are forever</i>

48
00:06:18,560 --> 00:06:23,873
<i>~ Sparkling round my little finger</i>

49
00:06:23,960 --> 00:06:28,431
<i>~ Unlike men, the diamonds linger</i>

50
00:06:28,520 --> 00:06:35,835
<i>~ Men are mere mortals</i>
<i>who are not worth going to your grave for</i>

51
00:06:37,360 --> 00:06:41,069
<i>~ I don't need love</i>

52
00:06:42,080 --> 00:06:46,631
<i>~ For what good would love do me?</i>

53
00:06:46,720 --> 00:06:50,508
<i>~ Diamonds never lie to me</i>

54
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:57,154
<i>~ For when love's gone</i>

55
00:06:57,240 --> 00:07:00,869
<i>~ They'll lustre on</i>

56
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:07,551
<i>~ Diamonds are forever, forever, forever</i>

57
00:07:07,760 --> 00:07:12,117
<i>~ Diamonds are forever, forever, forever</i>

58
00:07:12,200 --> 00:07:16,671
<i>~ Forever</i>

59
00:07:16,760 --> 00:07:20,389
<i>~ And ever</i>

60
00:07:29,200 --> 00:07:35,070
Star of South Africa:
83.5 carats rough, 47.5 carats cut.

61
00:07:35,160 --> 00:07:39,438
The Akbar Shah: 116 carats rough.

62
00:07:39,520 --> 00:07:44,230
- Are you paying attention, 007?
- The Akbar Shah: 116 carats rough.

63
00:07:45,160 --> 00:07:50,837
But there's no need to bring in our section
on a relatively simple smuggling matter.

64
00:07:50,920 --> 00:07:53,514
Sir Donald has convinced
the PM otherwise.

65
00:07:53,600 --> 00:07:57,798
May I remind you, 007,
that Blofeld's dead? Finished.

66
00:07:57,880 --> 00:08:03,193
The least we can expect from you now
is a little plain, solid work.

67
00:08:03,280 --> 00:08:06,033
Good morning, gentlemen.
Sir Donald will see you now.

68
00:08:06,120 --> 00:08:08,031
Thank you.

69
00:08:08,120 --> 00:08:10,793
Morning, Sir Donald.
This is Commander Bond.

70
00:08:10,880 --> 00:08:13,872
How do you do, Commander Bond?
Please sit down.

71
00:08:13,960 --> 00:08:16,428
- Sherry?
- Not for me. Doctor's orders.

72
00:08:16,520 --> 00:08:18,795
- Commander Bond?
- Yes, thank you.

73
00:08:18,880 --> 00:08:23,829
You've been on holiday, I understand.
Relaxing, I hope.

74
00:08:23,920 --> 00:08:26,992
Hardly relaxing, but most satisfying.

75
00:08:27,080 --> 00:08:29,071
- Cheers.
- Cheers.

76
00:08:31,440 --> 00:08:34,432
Pity about your liver.
It's an unusually fine Solera.

77
00:08:34,520 --> 00:08:38,513
- '51, I believe.
- There is no year for sherry, 007.

78
00:08:38,600 --> 00:08:43,799
I was referring to the original vintage
on which the sherry is based, sir.

79
00:08:45,320 --> 00:08:47,311
1851.

80
00:08:48,200 --> 00:08:50,873
- Unmistakable.
- Precisely.

81
00:08:50,960 --> 00:08:54,350
Tell me, Commander,
how far does your expertise

82
00:08:54,440 --> 00:08:56,874
extend into the field of diamonds?

83
00:08:58,080 --> 00:09:01,755
Hardest substance found in nature.
They cut glass. Suggest marriage.

84
00:09:01,840 --> 00:09:04,957
They've replaced a dog
as a girl's best friend. That's it.

85
00:09:05,040 --> 00:09:08,350
Refreshing to hear there's one subject
you're not an expert on.

86
00:09:08,440 --> 00:09:13,594
Yes, well, perhaps I'd better give you
a brief background into our problem.

87
00:09:13,680 --> 00:09:17,798
80 per cent of the world's diamonds
come from mines in South Africa.

88
00:09:17,880 --> 00:09:20,917
<i>Most are dug out of shafts</i>
<i>of diamond-bearing clay</i>

89
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:23,833
<i>at depths of up to 3000 feet.</i>

90
00:09:23,920 --> 00:09:27,879
<i>The whole process operates</i>
<i>under an airtight security system.</i>

91
00:09:27,960 --> 00:09:29,791
<i>It's an essential precaution,</i>

92
00:09:29,880 --> 00:09:36,228
<i>even though the industry prides itself on</i>
<i>the loyalty and devotion of its workers.</i>

93
00:09:36,320 --> 00:09:40,836
<i>Naturally the security measures</i>
<i>tend to ensure that loyalty,</i>

94
00:09:40,920 --> 00:09:44,469
<i>as do the extensive amenities</i>
<i>and social services we provide.</i>

95
00:09:44,560 --> 00:09:48,553
<i>There's a permanent staff</i>
<i>of doctors and nurses, even dentists.</i>

96
00:09:48,640 --> 00:09:53,475
<i>The whole process operates</i>
<i>under an airtight security system.</i>

97
00:09:53,560 --> 00:09:55,232
<i>It's a necessary precaution,</i>

98
00:09:55,320 --> 00:09:59,108
<i>even though the industry prides itself on</i>
<i>the loyalty and devotion of its workers.</i>

99
00:09:59,200 --> 00:10:01,191
Next.

100
00:10:05,560 --> 00:10:07,551
<i>(man)</i> The scorpion.

101
00:10:07,640 --> 00:10:10,108
Mother nature's finest killer, Mr Wint.

102
00:10:10,200 --> 00:10:14,990
One is never too old
to learn from a master, Mr Kidd.

103
00:10:36,320 --> 00:10:38,595
Dr Tynan? Good evening.

104
00:10:38,680 --> 00:10:42,832
- Who are you? And where is Joe?
- Joe couldn't make it tonight.

105
00:10:42,920 --> 00:10:46,799
I'm Mr Wint. This is Mr Kidd.

106
00:10:49,480 --> 00:10:51,471
I see.

107
00:11:03,600 --> 00:11:06,068
<i>(groans)</i>

108
00:11:06,160 --> 00:11:10,472
- What's the matter with him?
- My wisdom teeth. I haven't had 'em out.

109
00:11:10,560 --> 00:11:14,235
- Would you mind having a look, Doctor?
- Of course.

110
00:11:14,320 --> 00:11:18,393
I'm not going to hurt you. Just open.
No, no, no, open wide.

111
00:11:23,800 --> 00:11:25,950
Argh!

112
00:11:30,520 --> 00:11:36,516
Curious how everyone who touches
those diamonds seems to die.

113
00:11:49,600 --> 00:11:53,036
- <i>(man)</i> Stop right there. Who are you?
- Dr Tynan sent us.

114
00:11:53,120 --> 00:11:55,634
- Why didn't he come himself?
- He was taken sick.

115
00:11:55,720 --> 00:11:59,918
Bitten by the bug. He sent this for you.

116
00:12:10,880 --> 00:12:12,916
If God had wanted man to fly...

117
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:16,675
He would have given him wings, Mr Kidd.

118
00:12:26,640 --> 00:12:31,794
No security system is perfect. We've
always accepted a degree of smuggling.

119
00:12:31,880 --> 00:12:36,829
But over the past two years, despite all
our precautions, it's gone up alarmingly.

120
00:12:36,920 --> 00:12:41,391
- None of the stones reach the market.
- Sir Donald thinks someone's stockpiling.

121
00:12:41,480 --> 00:12:46,634
What concerns us is someone dumping
the stones on the market, or...

122
00:12:46,720 --> 00:12:49,553
Making you agree to perpetual blackmail.

123
00:12:49,640 --> 00:12:51,631
Exactly.

124
00:12:52,720 --> 00:12:57,919
What we need to know
is who the stockpilers are.

125
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:01,470
The letter U is for "umbrella".

126
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:04,275
We take it lest it rain.

127
00:13:04,360 --> 00:13:08,399
We hope we shan't want it
till we're home again.

128
00:13:08,480 --> 00:13:12,268
- Two men to see you, missy.
- <i>(teacher)</i> "Gentlemen", Joshua.

129
00:13:12,360 --> 00:13:17,115
I shan't be long, children.
Joshua is going to read you a story.

130
00:13:17,200 --> 00:13:21,671
How nice to see you again.
Where to this time?

131
00:13:21,760 --> 00:13:25,070
- Amsterdam.
- Amsterdam, how lovely.

132
00:13:25,160 --> 00:13:28,197
I'll have to bring back
some pictures for the children.

133
00:13:28,280 --> 00:13:31,352
Ask, and ye shall receive, Mrs Whistler.

134
00:13:34,120 --> 00:13:37,715
Thus endeth the lesson for today,
gentlemen.

135
00:13:37,800 --> 00:13:41,634
Several recent murders in South Africa
have complicated matters.

136
00:13:41,720 --> 00:13:44,757
If they shut down operations
before we discover them...

137
00:13:44,840 --> 00:13:49,197
It would be catastrophic for us
and for the government.

138
00:13:49,280 --> 00:13:53,193
- I've always fancied a trip to South Africa.
- You're going to Holland.

139
00:13:54,560 --> 00:13:58,838
For some time now, we've had our eyes
on a professional smuggler, Peter Franks.

140
00:13:58,920 --> 00:14:02,117
- He's due to leave for Amsterdam.
- Do we know his contacts?

141
00:14:02,200 --> 00:14:05,749
We do function in your absence,
Commander.

142
00:14:09,600 --> 00:14:11,795
Passport, sir?

143
00:14:13,520 --> 00:14:16,910
Mr Franks, there's a message
for you at Passport Control.

144
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:20,037
That door over there.
You can park your car outside.

145
00:14:20,120 --> 00:14:22,111
Thank you.

146
00:14:47,720 --> 00:14:50,917
Mr Franks, your passport is quite in order.

147
00:14:51,600 --> 00:14:57,311
Anyone seeing you in that outfit would
be discouraged from leaving the country.

148
00:14:57,400 --> 00:14:59,595
What can I bring you back from Holland?

149
00:14:59,680 --> 00:15:02,433
A diamond? In a ring?

150
00:15:05,480 --> 00:15:07,869
Would you settle for a tulip?

151
00:15:09,800 --> 00:15:10,835
Yes.

152
00:15:31,160 --> 00:15:36,075
<i>(woman on PA) Ahead is one of the oldest</i>
<i>bridges in Amsterdam: The Skinny Bridge.</i>

153
00:15:36,160 --> 00:15:41,154
<i>It was built 300 years ago by two sisters</i>
<i>who wanted to visit each other every day.</i>

154
00:15:41,240 --> 00:15:46,360
<i>Unfortunately they ran out of money. So</i>
<i>that is why it is called the Skinny Bridge.</i>

155
00:15:46,440 --> 00:15:52,549
<i>On your right, those beautiful old houses</i>
<i>can be seen in Rembrandt's paintings.</i>

156
00:15:52,640 --> 00:15:59,398
<i>And now, if you will look to your left</i>
<i>as we go down the Amstel, you can see...</i>

157
00:15:59,480 --> 00:16:01,277
<i>Oh.</i>

158
00:16:09,040 --> 00:16:12,749
Mrs Whistler did want some pictures
of the canals for the children.

159
00:16:12,840 --> 00:16:17,960
How kind of you, Mr Kidd.
The children will be so thrilled.

160
00:16:42,040 --> 00:16:45,237
- <i>(woman) Yes?</i>
- Franks. Peter Franks.

161
00:16:45,320 --> 00:16:47,072
<i>Come up. Third floor.</i>

162
00:17:04,800 --> 00:17:07,792
Make yourself at home.
I'll be out in a minute.

163
00:17:11,360 --> 00:17:14,591
Help yourself to a drink.

164
00:17:14,680 --> 00:17:16,671
Is Mr Case not at home?

165
00:17:16,760 --> 00:17:21,356
There is no Mr Case. The T is for Tiffany.

166
00:17:21,440 --> 00:17:25,797
Tiffany Case? Definitely distinctive.

167
00:17:25,880 --> 00:17:30,908
I was born there, on the first floor, while
my mother looked for a wedding ring.

168
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:34,390
I'm glad for your sake
it wasn't Van Cleef and Arpels.

169
00:17:38,320 --> 00:17:40,959
Weren't you a blonde when I came in?

170
00:17:41,040 --> 00:17:42,678
Could be.

171
00:17:42,760 --> 00:17:47,197
I tend to notice little things like that.
Whether a girl is a blonde or a brunette.

172
00:17:47,280 --> 00:17:50,192
And which do you prefer?

173
00:17:50,280 --> 00:17:53,590
Providing the collars and cuffs match...

174
00:17:53,680 --> 00:17:57,150
We'll talk about that later.
Let me have your glass.

175
00:17:57,240 --> 00:18:00,312
I'll get you some ice.

176
00:18:26,720 --> 00:18:30,679
That's quite a nice little nothing
you're almost wearing. I approve.

177
00:18:30,760 --> 00:18:35,754
I don't dress for the hired help.
Let's see your passport, Franks.

178
00:18:38,400 --> 00:18:42,712
Occupation: Transport consultant?
That's a little cute, isn't it?

179
00:18:43,440 --> 00:18:46,398
- I'll finish dressing.
- Don't. Not on my account.

180
00:19:26,800 --> 00:19:29,917
I don't care much for redheads.
Terrible tempers.

181
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:33,959
- But somehow it seems to suit you.
- It's my own.

182
00:19:34,040 --> 00:19:37,191
But it needs some soft lighting.
I know this restaurant...

183
00:19:37,280 --> 00:19:40,670
- I never mix business with pleasure.
- Neither do I.

184
00:19:40,760 --> 00:19:43,718
Good. We can start
by saving the cute remarks

185
00:19:43,800 --> 00:19:46,951
until after you get
the diamonds into Los Angeles.

186
00:19:47,040 --> 00:19:51,795
- Where are they now?
- Your problem is getting them in.

187
00:19:51,880 --> 00:19:55,316
- How much is there?
- 50,000 carats.

188
00:19:55,400 --> 00:19:59,837
At 142 carats an ounce, that's an awful lot
of ice. That won't be easy.

189
00:19:59,920 --> 00:20:02,798
That's why you're being paid 50 grand.

190
00:20:02,880 --> 00:20:05,838
What did you think it was going to be?
A pair of earrings?

191
00:20:05,920 --> 00:20:10,072
And, Franks, for God's sakes,
come up with something original.

192
00:20:15,360 --> 00:20:18,591
I've got to hand it to you, Q.
Quite ingenious.

193
00:20:18,680 --> 00:20:21,911
An obvious little notion.
Thought it might come in handy.

194
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:24,912
By the way, M's been trying
to get in touch with you.

195
00:20:25,000 --> 00:20:27,150
That Peter Franks has escaped.

196
00:20:27,680 --> 00:20:30,990
<i>He killed one of the guards</i>
<i>on the way up to London.</i>

197
00:20:31,080 --> 00:20:32,069
Hello?

198
00:20:33,520 --> 00:20:36,592
Hello? Are you there?

199
00:20:36,680 --> 00:20:37,908
Oh!

200
00:20:56,520 --> 00:20:58,272
- <i>(Tiffany) Yes?</i>
- Peter Franks.

201
00:20:58,360 --> 00:21:00,635
<i>Third floor.</i>

202
00:21:00,720 --> 00:21:03,188
- <i>Guten abend.</i>
- Good evening.

203
00:21:04,240 --> 00:21:06,390
<i>Bitte.</i>

204
00:21:06,800 --> 00:21:09,678
- <i>(German accent)</i> You are English?
- Yes, I'm English.

205
00:21:09,760 --> 00:21:11,955
I speak English.

206
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:16,594
- Who is your floor?
- Three, please.

207
00:23:37,040 --> 00:23:40,237
- Is he dead?
- I sincerely hope so.

208
00:23:47,120 --> 00:23:49,031
- Who is he?
- No idea.

209
00:23:49,120 --> 00:23:52,351
This chap's been following me
all day today.

210
00:23:56,480 --> 00:23:58,789
My God!

211
00:23:59,880 --> 00:24:02,269
You've just killed James Bond.

212
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:10,949
Is that who it was?
It just proves no one's indestructible.

213
00:24:11,040 --> 00:24:14,635
You don't kill James Bond and
sit waiting for the cops to arrive.

214
00:24:14,720 --> 00:24:17,109
We've got to get
the diamonds out of here fast.

215
00:24:17,200 --> 00:24:19,475
Where are they?

216
00:24:21,240 --> 00:24:24,596
A little old lady dropped them by
yesterday morning.

217
00:24:26,280 --> 00:24:28,271
Priceless.

218
00:24:30,600 --> 00:24:33,910
I think we ought to let Mr Bond
carry the load from here on out.

219
00:24:46,680 --> 00:24:51,629
It's funny. All the things one wanted to
say to one's brother when it's all too late.

220
00:24:51,720 --> 00:24:54,393
Let me assure you
of our deepest condolences.

221
00:24:54,480 --> 00:24:57,472
Would you please board the aircraft?

222
00:24:59,520 --> 00:25:02,990
- We were inseparable, you know.
- Please, Mr Franks.

223
00:25:04,520 --> 00:25:11,312
<i>(air stewardess) Lufthansa announce the</i>
<i>departure of flight, LH450 to Los Angeles.</i>

224
00:25:13,920 --> 00:25:19,916
<i>Will you please fasten your seatbelts?</i>
<i>No smoking until airborne. Thank you.</i>

225
00:25:21,680 --> 00:25:26,151
They're both aboard. I must say,
Miss Case seems quite attractive.

226
