The next link in the pipeline.

456
00:48:58,400 --> 00:49:00,630
What are you talking about?

457
00:49:00,720 --> 00:49:04,156
Poor Plenty must have
stumbled in here looking for you.

458
00:49:04,240 --> 00:49:06,754
I don't believe you.

459
00:49:06,840 --> 00:49:10,879
A dentist is dead in South Africa.
That little old lady in Amsterdam.

460
00:49:10,960 --> 00:49:15,158
Shady got his last night.
They've missed me once, and you're next.

461
00:49:15,760 --> 00:49:19,275
- Who's your connection?
- You sound like a cop...

462
00:49:19,360 --> 00:49:24,388
- Who's your connection?
- All I know is voices on a phone.

463
00:49:24,480 --> 00:49:27,711
They got me this place
and told me to wait for instructions.

464
00:49:27,800 --> 00:49:31,156
You'd find it hard to hear underwater.
Where's the stuff?

465
00:49:31,240 --> 00:49:35,074
Who are you? You're not a cop
and you're not Peter Franks.

466
00:49:35,160 --> 00:49:38,038
You're not the type
to turn the other cheek. Where is it?

467
00:49:38,360 --> 00:49:42,672
<i>(PA) Eastern Airlines announce the arrival</i>
<i>of their flight, 112 from Los Angeles,</i>

468
00:49:42,760 --> 00:49:45,320
<i>gate seven.</i>

469
00:50:14,040 --> 00:50:16,031
Thank you.

470
00:50:46,000 --> 00:50:47,638
- Fill it up, please.
- OK.

471
00:50:47,720 --> 00:50:52,077
- It's Bert Saxby.
- He's Willard Whyte's right-hand man.

472
00:50:56,840 --> 00:50:59,149
Do you see the top? The penthouse?

473
00:50:59,240 --> 00:51:02,869
They say Willard Whyte hasn't
set foot out of there in three years,

474
00:51:02,960 --> 00:51:05,235
and no one has seen him. No one.

475
00:51:09,600 --> 00:51:12,160
- How much is that?
- Did you pay for this?

476
00:51:12,600 --> 00:51:14,830
Cut him off.

477
00:51:23,360 --> 00:51:25,555
Hey, Curly. What about my stamps?

478
00:51:25,640 --> 00:51:27,790
Where are you going?
Are you mad? Let me by.

479
00:51:27,880 --> 00:51:30,519
Stamps? You ain't got no gas yet. OK?

480
00:51:30,600 --> 00:51:33,990
- OK. So shove a coupla gallons in.
- Well, back it up.

481
00:51:35,280 --> 00:51:36,918
<i>(sounds horn)</i>

482
00:51:37,000 --> 00:51:41,039
Keep leaning on that tooter,
and you're gonna get a shot in the mouth.

483
00:51:41,120 --> 00:51:45,113
- Come on, lady, move it.
- OK, lady, you win. You win.

484
00:51:45,200 --> 00:51:46,838
<i>(car horns)</i>

485
00:51:46,920 --> 00:51:51,710
- Will someone move that car?
- Do what he says.

486
00:51:52,480 --> 00:51:55,040
Hey! I wanted high-test.

487
00:51:56,000 --> 00:51:59,197
Forget it, Curly.
You had your chance and you blew it.

488
00:53:03,080 --> 00:53:04,479
OK, Professor.

489
00:54:24,320 --> 00:54:25,799
- Hello.
- Hi.

490
00:54:25,880 --> 00:54:29,077
- I haven't seen you here before.
- Klaus Hergersheimer.

491
00:54:29,160 --> 00:54:32,118
- New here?
- I've been here three years. G Section.

492
00:54:32,200 --> 00:54:34,589
How are things in G Section?

493
00:54:35,440 --> 00:54:39,752
Still the same old grind. Checking
radiation shields for replacement.

494
00:54:39,840 --> 00:54:42,673
By the way, where's yours?

495
00:54:42,760 --> 00:54:46,275
I've been waiting a couple of days
for you guys to deliver them.

496
00:54:46,360 --> 00:54:49,955
Gee, I'm sorry.
You should have given us a phone call.

497
00:54:50,040 --> 00:54:53,874
I've got one here.
Lucky for you, I carry spares.

498
00:54:53,960 --> 00:54:57,191
You keep that on.
You can't be too careful about radiation.

499
00:54:57,280 --> 00:55:01,751
- Absolutely. I feel much safer with this on.
- See you around.

500
00:55:26,120 --> 00:55:28,350
Who are you? What do you want?

501
00:55:28,440 --> 00:55:32,752
Klaus Hergersheimer. G Section.
Just checking on radiation shields.

502
00:55:32,840 --> 00:55:36,628
- Now, let me see. You are...?
- Professor Dr Metz.

503
00:55:36,720 --> 00:55:39,154
Our shields are fine. Now get out.

504
00:55:39,240 --> 00:55:43,950
I'm sorry.
It won't take a moment, but I must verify.

505
00:55:44,040 --> 00:55:47,476
Metz. How do you spell it?

506
00:55:47,560 --> 00:55:50,677
Will you please leave, you irritating man?

507
00:55:50,760 --> 00:55:54,070
Doctor, there's no reason
to run down the little people.

508
00:55:54,160 --> 00:55:58,438
G Section may not be as important
as you are, but we do have our orders.

509
00:55:58,520 --> 00:56:01,159
- Dr Metz, Willard Whyte for you.
- Right.

510
00:56:01,240 --> 00:56:03,231
Out, out.

511
00:56:06,880 --> 00:56:08,677
Hello, WW.

512
00:56:08,760 --> 00:56:11,957
Yes, it's finally here.

513
00:56:12,040 --> 00:56:14,429
Quite enough for completion.

514
00:56:16,280 --> 00:56:20,512
We'll be through shortly.
No. No problems at all.

515
00:56:27,880 --> 00:56:30,633
- Now will you get out of here?
- Certainly, Doctor.

516
00:56:30,720 --> 00:56:33,757
I've seen everything I need to see.

517
00:56:33,840 --> 00:56:36,115
Thank you very much.

518
00:56:38,840 --> 00:56:41,752
Hi. Sorry to bother you.
I'm Klaus Hergersheimer.

519
00:56:42,520 --> 00:56:44,988
G Section.

520
00:56:47,240 --> 00:56:49,435
Checking radiation shields?

521
00:57:01,080 --> 00:57:03,036
<i>(alarm)</i>

522
00:57:03,960 --> 00:57:06,235
There he is, behind the rock. Come on!

523
00:57:08,880 --> 00:57:13,351
<i>(PA) What the hell is this?</i>
<i>Amateur night? Stop him, Harry.</i>

524
00:57:18,080 --> 00:57:21,789
<i>Get him off that machine. That isn't a toy.</i>
<i>Get out of that moon buggy!</i>

525
00:57:49,760 --> 00:57:52,149
It's gone berserk.

526
00:57:53,480 --> 00:57:56,472
- Stop.
- What do you think you're doing? Hey!

527
00:59:32,720 --> 00:59:34,711
That way.

528
01:00:31,000 --> 01:00:32,991
- What happened?
- Get in.

529
01:00:33,080 --> 01:00:36,868
If you see a mad professor
in a minibus, just smile.

530
01:00:53,680 --> 01:00:56,797
Fred, get the sheriff's office.

531
01:01:05,000 --> 01:01:09,312
You can drop me off at the next corner.
This whole thing is getting out of hand.

532
01:01:09,400 --> 01:01:13,916
No regrets, but when you steal moon
machines from Willard Whyte, goodbye.

533
01:01:14,000 --> 01:01:17,549
Just relax. I have a friend named Felix
who can fix anything.

534
01:01:17,640 --> 01:01:20,154
Is he married?

535
01:01:22,680 --> 01:01:25,319
There goes that son-of-a-bitchin' saboteur.

536
01:01:25,400 --> 01:01:27,391
<i>(siren)</i>

537
01:01:36,320 --> 01:01:39,710
Relax. You've got a friend
named Felix who can fix anything.

538
01:01:39,800 --> 01:01:41,950
Unfortunately, so can Willard Whyte.

539
01:01:48,200 --> 01:01:50,395
Why, you dirty...

540
01:01:52,480 --> 01:01:53,629
<i>(siren)</i>

541
01:04:04,600 --> 01:04:06,670
Come in, Larry. Larry?

542
01:04:07,360 --> 01:04:08,952
<i>Larry?</i>

543
01:04:09,040 --> 01:04:11,031
<i>Go get him, Larry.</i>

544
01:04:13,280 --> 01:04:15,635
- I think Larry got him.
- Sheriff...

545
01:04:15,720 --> 01:04:18,234
Attaboy, Larry. Come in. Larry?

546
01:04:18,320 --> 01:04:19,912
Sheriff...

547
01:04:25,720 --> 01:04:27,711
<i>(siren)</i>

548
01:04:35,200 --> 01:04:37,555
I got you now.

549
01:04:39,720 --> 01:04:41,119
Lean over.

550
01:05:14,400 --> 01:05:19,315
<i>(Tiffany)</i> Why are we suddenly staying
in the bridal suite of the Whyte House?

551
01:05:19,400 --> 01:05:23,279
In order to form
a more perfect union, sweetheart.

552
01:05:23,360 --> 01:05:25,032
James...

553
01:05:25,120 --> 01:05:27,759
May I finally call you James?

554
01:05:30,920 --> 01:05:33,912
What's going to happen to me?

555
01:05:35,520 --> 01:05:37,988
You did talk to your friend Felix
about me?

556
01:05:38,080 --> 01:05:41,117
- Uh-huh.
- Well, what did he say?

557
01:05:41,200 --> 01:05:44,510
Something about 20 years to life.
Nothing important.

558
01:05:44,600 --> 01:05:49,720
- 20 years to life?
- Relax, I'm on top of the situation.

559
01:05:59,720 --> 01:06:01,438
Mr and Mrs Jones?

560
01:06:01,520 --> 01:06:05,752
Yes. That's the name on the register,
Mr Leiter. What's the score with WW?

561
01:06:05,840 --> 01:06:08,912
- Washington says no go. We sit still.
- Sit still?

562
01:06:09,000 --> 01:06:13,790
And Miss Tiffany Case "Jones" has
a lifetime reservation at another hotel.

563
01:06:13,880 --> 01:06:16,553
The kind the government... runs.

564
01:06:16,640 --> 01:06:20,553
I'm cooperating, Mr Leiter. Really I am.

565
01:06:20,640 --> 01:06:22,870
I can vouch for that.

566
01:06:22,960 --> 01:06:26,430
This is not the real White House
and he's not the president.

567
01:06:26,520 --> 01:06:29,751
- Why don't we just see him?
- The president I can get you in to see.

568
01:06:29,840 --> 01:06:33,389
But until Washington believes
Whyte's a thief, that's the way it is.

569
01:06:33,480 --> 01:06:37,837
In the mean time, I'm sure
you and Mrs Jones can amuse yourselves.

570
01:06:37,920 --> 01:06:41,879
And just to make sure you're not
disturbed, I have a man upstairs.

571
01:06:41,960 --> 01:06:45,509
And Hamilton is right out here.

572
01:06:45,600 --> 01:06:47,591
So long, James.

573
01:06:47,680 --> 01:06:50,069
- Well, that's a switch.
- What's that?

574
01:06:50,160 --> 01:06:53,391
The wolf being guarded
by the three little pigs.

575
01:06:54,920 --> 01:06:57,309
I won't be long, darling.

576
01:06:57,400 --> 01:06:59,789
Where are you going?

577
01:06:59,880 --> 01:07:03,270
I'm just popping upstairs for a moment.

578
01:07:10,000 --> 01:07:14,790
- Sixteenth floor?
- <i>(man)</i> No, lady. Starlight Lounge only.

579
01:07:14,880 --> 01:07:18,270
OK, folks, stand clear of the doors.
Here we go.

580
01:07:55,560 --> 01:07:59,997
<i>(man)</i> Starlight Lounge to the left.
Express to street level only, folks.

581
01:08:00,080 --> 01:08:03,914
OK. Stand clear of the doors. Here we go.

582
01:10:29,640 --> 01:10:32,552
<i>(Whyte) Howdy. Welcome.</i>
<i>We've been expectin' you.</i>

583
01:10:32,640 --> 01:10:36,474
<i>You got any personal business</i>
<i>to take care of in there, go right ahead.</i>

584
01:10:36,560 --> 01:10:42,032
<i>I suspect you're wearin' a hogleg. Would</i>
<i>you mind standin' up and takin' it off?</i>

585
01:10:45,240 --> 01:10:49,677
<i>Oh, isn't that nice?</i>
<i>You are a pleasant fella.</i>

586
01:10:50,800 --> 01:10:55,112
<i>Why don't you just come on in, son?</i>
<i>Relax, make yourself comfortable.</i>

587
01:10:55,200 --> 01:10:58,192
<i>That's good. Right on over there.</i>

588
01:11:17,800 --> 01:11:20,997
- Good evening, Mr Bond.
- Blofeld.

589
01:11:23,440 --> 01:11:25,237
Good evening, 007.

590
01:11:28,800 --> 01:11:33,157
Double jeopardy, Mr Bond. You killed
my only other double, I'm afraid.

591
01:11:33,240 --> 01:11:38,439
After his death, volunteers were
understandably rather scarce.

592
01:11:38,920 --> 01:11:41,229
Such a pity. All that time and expense,

593
01:11:41,320 --> 01:11:44,517
simply to provide you
with one mock-heroic moment.

594
01:11:44,600 --> 01:11:46,670
<i>(phone rings)</i>

595
01:11:51,600 --> 01:11:54,160
<i>(Southern accent)</i> Willard Whyte speakin'.

596
01:11:54,240 --> 01:11:56,390
Yes, Governor, I got your message.

597
01:11:56,480 --> 01:12:00,553
No, I'm afraid a personal appearance
is quite out of the question.

598
01:12:00,640 --> 01:12:04,997
I'll send a deposition to the committee.
Thank you, Governor.

599
01:12:07,360 --> 01:12:11,114
- That's a neat trick.
- A voice box, Mr Bond.

600
01:12:11,200 --> 01:12:15,159
Science was never my strong suit,
but the principle is easy enough.

601
01:12:15,240 --> 01:12:20,837
Someone's voice patterns and resonance
stored in a small oral-signature tape.

602
01:12:20,920 --> 01:12:24,879
And a miniature, transistorised version
is installed in his neck.

603
01:12:24,960 --> 01:12:27,110
Or is it his neck? I never can remember.

604
01:12:27,200 --> 01:12:29,953
Anyway, no matter. We both sound alike.

605
01:12:32,000 --> 01:12:34,594
My congratulations to you both.

606
01:12:38,120 --> 01:12:41,032
Nice little company.

607
01:12:41,120 --> 01:12:45,113
Explosives, oil, electronics,
houses, aviation.

608
01:12:45,200 --> 01:12:48,237
I've done well with it.
Tried to cut some of the fat off.

609
01:12:48,320 --> 01:12:52,393
Actually, Mr Whyte's
a splendid administrator. <i>(laughs)</i>

610
01:12:52,480 --> 01:12:55,233
- Damn thing runs itself.
- I suppose you killed him.

611
01:12:55,320 --> 01:12:59,836
Nothing so melodramatic. I'm simply
holding him in cold storage, so to speak.

612
01:12:59,920 --> 01:13:03,879
An insurance policy against
any outside interference with my plans.

613
01:13:03,960 --> 01:13:08,033
Hm. The ideal kidnap victim.
No one's seen the man for five years.

614
01:13:08,120 --> 01:13:12,398
- So who'd miss someone who's missing?
- How clever you are, Mr Bond.

615
01:13:12,480 --> 01:13:16,917
Nice to see you haven't lost
that fine mental edge, 007.

616
01:13:17,000 --> 01:13:21,949
Please don't get any foolish notions.
That missile is not a practical weapon.

617
01:13:23,840 --> 01:13:26,912
It's hardly worth the effort.

618
01:13:27,000 --> 01:13:30,037
After all, I wouldn't know
which one of you to kill.

619
01:13:30,120 --> 01:13:32,680
We appreciate
your predicament, Mr Bond.

620
01:13:32,760 --> 01:13:34,671
We deeply sympathise.

621
01:13:41,200 --> 01:13:43,316
<i>(gun is cocked)</i>

622
01:13:52,920 --> 01:13:55,593
Right idea, Mr Bond.

623
01:13:55,680 --> 01:13:57,830
But wrong pussy.

624
01:13:57,920 --> 01:14:02,038
I do so enjoy our little visits, Mr Bond.

625
01:14:02,120 --> 01:14:07,274
However potentially painful they may be.
I'm afraid this one has come to an end.

626
01:14:07,360 --> 01:14:10,557
What do you intend to do
with those diamonds?

627
01:14:10,640 --> 01:14:12,756
An excellent question.

628
01:14:12,840 --> 01:14:16,628
And one which will be hanging
on the lips of the world quite soon.

629
01:14:16,720 --> 01:14:20,508
If I were to break the news to anyone,
it would be to you first, Mr Bond.

630
01:14:20,600 --> 01:14:25,469
But it's late, I'm tired,
and there's so much left to do.

631
01:14:28,040 --> 01:14:30,031
Good night, Mr Bond.

632
01:14:37,280 --> 01:14:40,033
Well, go on, go on. It's merely a lift.

633
01:14:40,640 --> 01:14:43,677
Or perhaps I should say "elevator".

634
01:14:44,680 --> 01:14:50,471
You'll find it much more convenient than
mountaineering outside the Whyte House.

635
01:14:51,480 --> 01:14:55,792
You press L, Mr Bond.
The word "lobby" begins with L.

636
01:15:07,920 --> 01:15:09,717
<i>(hissing)</i>

637
01:15:13,400 --> 01:15:15,391
<i>(Bond collapses)</i>

638
01:15:26,040 --> 01:15:29,589
If at first you don't succeed, Mr Kidd...

639
01:15:29,680 --> 01:15:32,274
Try, try again, Mr Wint.

640
01:15:46,920 --> 01:15:49,115
<i>(bottle breaks)</i>

641
01:17:07,640 --> 01:17:09,631
<i>(they chuckle)</i>

642
01:18:23,400 --> 01:18:24,833
<i>(squeaking)</i>

643
01:18:32,760 --> 01:18:35,957
One of us smells like a tart's handkerchief.

644
01:18:42,560 --> 01:18:45,677
I'm afraid it's me.
Sorry about that, old boy.

645
01:18:45,760 --> 01:18:48,035
<i>(rat hisses)</i>

646
01:19:23,880 --> 01:19:26,997
<i>(man)</i> I don't mind the machine
breaking down twice a day,

647
01:19:27,080 --> 01:19:32,074
but why the hell does it always have to be
500 yards away from the nearest hatch?

648
01:19:34,160 --> 01:19:37,948
All right, Charlie,
it's your turn to play hunchback.

649
01:19:41,080 --> 01:19:42,593
Thank you very much.

650
01:19:42,680 --> 01:19:46,753
I was walking my rat
and I seem to have lost my way.

651
01:19:49,240 --> 01:19:51,196
<i>(phone rings)</i>

652
01:19:51,280 --> 01:19:54,955
- <i>(Southern accent)</i> Willard Whyte.
- This is Bert.

653
01:19:56,240 --> 01:19:59,038
<i>(like Bert)</i> We got a problem.

654
01:20:00,240 --> 01:20:05,519
<i>(as Blofeld) What's the matter with your</i>
<i>voice, Bert? Have you got a cold?</i>

655
01:20:05,600 --> 01:20:09,673
<i>(more like Bert)</i> Never mind about that.
I just saw James Bond in the casino.

656
01:20:09,760 --> 01:20:12,638
- That's impossible.
- <i>Yeah? Have a look for yourself.</i>

657
01:20:12,720 --> 01:20:17,714
Hey, listen, if he's half the genius
they say he is, we're in for real trouble.

658
01:20:17,800 --> 01:20:21,315
- <i>Now calm down, Bert.</i>
- It's a cinch he's not working alone.

659
01:20:21,400 --> 01:20:25,951
This place must be crawling with agents.
I think we should move Willard Whyte.

660
01:20:26,040 --> 01:20:29,476
<i>Nonsense. Mr Whyte is perfectly safe</i>
<i>at his own summerhouse.</i>

661
01:20:29,560 --> 01:20:32,154
It's on the ridge,
about ten miles out of town.

662
01:20:32,240 --> 01:20:35,710
<i>I'm a little surprised, Bert.</i>
<i>It's not like you to panic.</i>

663
01:20:35,800 --> 01:20:39,190
I don't enjoy messing around
with a guy as tough as James Bond.

664
01:20:39,280 --> 01:20:43,193
Never mind James Bond.
You get down to that house.

665
01:20:43,280 --> 01:20:47,319
I'm afraid Mr Whyte has suddenly
outgrown his usefulness. Do it cleanly.

666
01:20:47,400 --> 01:20:51,393
<i>(as Bert)</i> Don't worry.
Just leave everything to me.

667
01:20:52,400 --> 01:20:56,359
<i>(as Bond)</i> That ridiculous contraption
actually seems to work, Q.

668
01:20:56,440 --> 01:20:59,113
- You've surpassed yourself.
- Not a bit of it.

669
01:20:59,200 --> 01:21:01,919
Made one of these
for the kids last Christmas.

670
01:21:02,000 --> 01:21:07,199
James and I are heading for the house. Hit
the penthouse as soon as we find Whyte.

671
01:21:07,280 --> 01:21:09,271
<i>(Blofeld)</i> Let me speak to Metz.

672
01:21:09,760 --> 01:21:15,278
There's a change. Push all plans forward
by 24 hours. I'm joining you immediately.

673
01:21:21,760 --> 01:21:25,673
Give me five minutes to get up there
and five minutes to find Whyte.

674
01:21:26,400 --> 01:21:29,437
Are you sure you know
what you're doing?

675
01:21:29,520 --> 01:21:32,512
Ask me again in ten minutes' time.

676
01:21:34,280 --> 01:21:37,272
Tell Maxwell to stand by
to hit the penthouse.

677
01:22:27,520 --> 01:22:30,239
Well, hi there.

678
01:22:34,200 --> 01:22:35,792
I'm Bambi.

679
01:22:37,400 --> 01:22:39,709
Good morning, Bambi.

680
01:22:39,800 --> 01:22:44,510
And I'm Thumper.
Is there something we can do for you?

681
01:22:44,600 --> 01:22:47,672
I can think of several things offhand,

682
01:22:47,760 --> 01:22:50,513
but at the moment
I'm looking for Willard Whyte.

683
01:22:50,600 --> 01:22:54,195
Oh, Willie. Why, he's right out there.

684
01:22:56,240 --> 01:23:00,313
And that's all there is to it?

685
01:23:00,400 --> 01:23:02,595
Not quite.

686
01:23:02,680 --> 01:23:06,468
First we're gonna have a ball.

687
01:23:11,240 --> 01:23:13,595
All yours, Bambi.

688
01:23:28,960 --> 01:23:30,791
You're on again, Bambi.

689
01:23:36,040 --> 01:23:37,837
Thumper.

690
01:24:17,960 --> 01:24:19,951
<i>(both)</i> Yah!

691
01:25:00,080 --> 01:25:01,593
Hello, Felix.

692
01:25:01,680 --> 01:25:04,911
Wouldn't you know it?
Willard Whyte is about to be executed,

693
01:25:05,000 --> 01:25:08,629
and guess who's giving
breaststroke lessons.

694
01:25:08,720 --> 01:25:12,998
- Where the hell is Whyte?
- I haven't found out yet.

695
01:25:13,080 --> 01:25:15,071
<i>(both gasp)</i>

696
01:25:16,560 --> 01:25:19,279
Still haven't found out.

697
01:25:25,440 --> 01:25:27,431
Right.

698
01:25:51,240 --> 01:25:53,993
FBI? CIA?

699
01:25:54,080 --> 01:25:57,470
No. British Intelligence, Mr Whyte.
James Bond.

700
01:26:00,320 --> 01:26:03,153
I see you've met my friends
Bambi and Thumper.

701
01:26:03,240 --> 01:26:05,959
Yes, we did have a bit of a chat.

702
01:26:06,040 --> 01:26:09,237
What the hell's happened to me
and what can I do about it?

703
01:26:09,320 --> 01:26:13,233
Let's get out of here first
and I'll explain it to you en route.

704
01:26:14,040 --> 01:26:16,634
- Tell Maxwell to hit the penthouse...
- <i>(gunshot)</i>

705
01:26:17,680 --> 01:26:19,671
<i>(machine-gun fire)</i>

706
01:26:24,600 --> 01:26:26,955
Argh!

707
01:26:30,440 --> 01:26:32,635
Saxby.

708
01:26:32,720 --> 01:26:35,871
- Bert Saxby?
- Yeah.

709
01:26:35,960 --> 01:26:39,191
Tell him he's fired.

710
01:26:52,840 --> 01:26:55,115
Hi there, Mr Q. Are you having any luck?

711
01:26:55,200 --> 01:27:00,399
- I'm being somewhat successful, thanks.
- Listen, Mr Q, I was wondering.

712
01:27:00,480 --> 01:27:04,712
Have you heard any talk
about me from Felix or James?

713
01:27:04,800 --> 01:27:06,791
No, I'm afraid not.

714
01:27:06,880 --> 01:27:12,034
I guess I'm working for the good guys
now, but I'm still two steps away from jail.

715
01:27:12,120 --> 01:27:16,238
I thought you might be able
to put in a good word.

716
01:27:24,920 --> 01:27:27,434
That's unbelievable.

717
01:27:28,080 --> 01:27:33,837
An electromagnetic RPM controller.
Been aching to give it a try.

718
01:27:33,920 --> 01:27:37,754
You see, pressure on the case here
when the desired symbols appear,

719
01:27:37,840 --> 01:27:44,439
this causes the rotation of the cylinders to
stutter at the precise moment needed to...

720
01:27:52,800 --> 01:27:55,109
Cab, lady?

721
01:28:02,360 --> 01:28:05,511
Well, well, well.
Look what the cat dragged in.

722
01:28:05,600 --> 01:28:07,795
I'm delighted to meet you, Miss Case.

723
01:28:07,880 --> 01:28:11,668
I'd so dreaded the prospect of
making this tedious journey alone.

724
01:28:24,240 --> 01:28:28,631
It was right here.
About six feet high, with a solar panel.

725
01:28:28,720 --> 01:28:32,508
- It had these aerofoils that seemed to...
- Draw it for me.

726
01:28:32,600 --> 01:28:35,114
Was Dr Metz on your payroll, Mr Whyte?

727
01:28:35,200 --> 01:28:38,078
No, but I heard of him.
Everybody in our business has.

728
01:28:38,160 --> 01:28:41,197
The world's leading expert
on laser refraction.

729
01:28:41,280 --> 01:28:43,874
A committed idealist to peace.

730
01:28:43,960 --> 01:28:48,590
And how in the hell Blofeld got
his hooks in him, I will never know.

731
01:28:48,680 --> 01:28:51,194
How did he get security clearance
to work here?

732
01:28:51,280 --> 01:28:54,636
From you, sir.
I talked to you personally about it.

733
01:28:54,720 --> 01:28:57,029
I even recognised your voice just now.

734
01:28:57,120 --> 01:29:02,831
I'm sure I told you not to keep the usual
duplicate microfilm records of the project.

735
01:29:02,920 --> 01:29:05,070
Exactly.

736
01:29:05,160 --> 01:29:08,596
Tom, what did <i>I tell you to do with this?

737
01:29:08,680 --> 01:29:10,910
Send it to Vandenberg.

738
01:29:11,000 --> 01:29:14,117
Well, get 'em on the phone, now.

739
01:29:17,840 --> 01:29:19,637
<i>(phone rings)</i>

740
01:29:19,720 --> 01:29:21,517
Yeah?

741
01:29:21,600 --> 01:29:24,512
You won't believe this.
Willard Whyte for you.

742
01:29:24,600 --> 01:29:27,114
Wow.
This is a real honour, sir.

743
01:29:27,200 --> 01:29:30,033
Shove it. Where's that satellite
I sent down there?

744
01:29:30,120 --> 01:29:32,111
Blasted off 24 minutes ago, sir.

745
01:29:36,120 --> 01:29:40,591
Perfect trajectory. All systems go.
We expect to enter orbit right on the nose.

746
01:29:46,880 --> 01:29:50,555
- Wait. Something's happened.
- Just a moment, Mr Whyte.

747
01:29:50,640 --> 01:29:52,835
The scanners have gone crazy.

748
01:29:52,920 --> 01:29:55,639
- Premature separation.
- It doesn't make sense.

749
01:30:07,360 --> 01:30:09,749
Stand by to abort.

750
01:30:12,840 --> 01:30:15,274
- We can't control it, sir.
- Abort it.

751
01:30:16,320 --> 01:30:18,072
- It's negative.
- We can't.

752
01:30:18,160 --> 01:30:21,152
Something's taken over
the guidance systems.

753
01:30:21,240 --> 01:30:26,189
- It's as if it had a will of its own.
- And there's not a damn thing we can do.

754
01:30:26,280 --> 01:30:28,475
We're working on it. I'll call you back.

755
01:30:31,440 --> 01:30:35,592
Well, whatever it is,
your friend Blofeld's controllin' it now.

756
01:30:41,800 --> 01:30:45,839
A vast supply of diamonds manipulated
by an expert in light refraction.

757
01:30:45,920 --> 01:30:48,309
The first beam was generated
through a diamond,

758
01:30:48,400 --> 01:30:54,509
and if Metz deserves his reputation, the
power of that thing could be incredible.

759
01:30:54,600 --> 01:30:56,591
And Blofeld's got it.

760
01:30:59,560 --> 01:31:02,757
- Where is it now?
- <i>(man) Approaching North Dakota.</i>

761
01:31:02,840 --> 01:31:06,594
- Alert Strategic Air Command.
- Give me an open line to SAC.

762
01:31:07,920 --> 01:31:11,799
<i>(PA) Attention all personnel.</i>
<i>Attention all personnel.</i>

763
01:31:11,880 --> 01:31:16,476
<i>We have a red alert.</i>
<i>Stand by for emergency procedure.</i>

764
01:31:31,320 --> 01:31:33,311
<i>(phone rings)</i>

765
01:31:34,440 --> 01:31:36,431
Willard Whyte.

766
01:31:40,280 --> 01:31:42,271
Yes, General.

767
01:31:45,160 --> 01:31:50,996
One of our missiles just accidentally
blew up in North Dakota.

768
01:31:51,080 --> 01:31:53,833
Whatever's happenin',
Mr Bond, has started.

769
01:32:13,840 --> 01:32:17,913
- Is this your herd?
- Mr Whyte, phone call from Washington.

770
01:32:18,000 --> 01:32:20,992
- I'll catch it in the john.
- What about Blofeld?

771
01:32:21,080 --> 01:32:24,072
- Not a trace, but we found a tunnel.
- Where's Tiffany?

772
01:32:24,160 --> 01:32:28,950
Do you mind if we find Blofeld first?
Come on, let's hit that tunnel.

773
01:32:45,200 --> 01:32:47,191
Argh!

774
01:32:54,960 --> 01:32:58,999
Well, Washington just got word
from your friend with the cat.

775
01:32:59,080 --> 01:33:02,868
Would you believe that this whole
country is bein' held for ransom

776
01:33:02,960 --> 01:33:05,838
and we've got
till noon tomorrow to pay up?

777
01:33:05,920 --> 01:33:09,913
So that's it, then.
Well, I'm sure you won't be alone.

778
01:33:10,000 --> 01:33:15,996
An international auction, with nuclear
supremacy goin' to the highest bidder.

779
01:33:17,400 --> 01:33:20,597
Tell me, what does he need
to control that satellite?

780
01:33:20,680 --> 01:33:25,196
A simple set of tapes fed into a computer
bank. All he really needs is a building.

781
01:33:25,280 --> 01:33:29,159
And these tapes? Large or small?

782
01:33:29,240 --> 01:33:34,951
Conceivably any size,
from six inches to a cassette.

783
01:33:35,040 --> 01:33:38,032
Assuming he's still using
your empire as a cover,

784
01:33:38,120 --> 01:33:40,395
Blofeld could be anywhere on this map.

785
01:33:40,480 --> 01:33:44,314
From Alaska to Florida,
from Maine to Oregon.

786
01:33:44,400 --> 01:33:47,472
From Texas to Baja California.

787
01:33:49,520 --> 01:33:51,511
Baja?

788
01:33:52,200 --> 01:33:55,317
I haven't got anything at Baja.

789
01:34:01,040 --> 01:34:05,636
<i>(radio) There is still no official explanation</i>
<i>of the simultaneous nuclear accidents</i>

790
01:34:05,720 --> 01:34:07,358
<i>in North Dakota and Russia.</i>

791
01:34:07,440 --> 01:34:11,558
<i>Presidential news secretary John Fenner</i>
<i>has refused comment on a report</i>

792
01:34:11,640 --> 01:34:15,076
<i>that a meeting of the Joint Chiefs</i>
<i>of Staff is in session.</i>

793
01:34:15,160 --> 01:34:19,438
<i>It is believed the United States and</i>
<i>the Soviet Union have assured each other</i>

794
01:34:19,520 --> 01:34:22,592
<i>that no offensive action</i>
<i>has been taken by either nation.</i>

795
01:34:22,680 --> 01:34:28,198
<i>Reports of another nuclear accident</i>
<i>in Red China are as yet unconfirmed...</i>

796
01:34:28,280 --> 01:34:30,919
Two more submarines
have taken up position.

797
01:34:31,000 --> 01:34:33,560
Will those military aircraft
stand off forever?

798
01:34:33,640 --> 01:34:37,349
What if they won't accept our ultimatum?
What if they decide to attack?

799
01:34:37,440 --> 01:34:42,195
Calm yourself, Metz. This farcical show
of force was only to be expected.

800
01:34:42,280 --> 01:34:46,990
The Great Powers flexing their muscles
like so many impotent beach boys.

801
01:34:47,080 --> 01:34:51,551
I regret my threat to destroy a major city
unless they give in, but there it is,

802
01:34:51,640 --> 01:34:55,838
the nuclear powers, like all bullies,
can only be intimidated by force.

803
01:34:55,920 --> 01:34:59,071
- But how can...
- There's still an hour left to reply.

804
01:34:59,160 --> 01:35:02,152
One hour for both of us
to achieve our common dream:

805
01:35:02,240 --> 01:35:06,313
Total disarmament
and peace for the world.

806
01:35:08,120 --> 01:35:11,237
- Sir, there's a single plane approaching.
- Range?

807
01:35:11,320 --> 01:35:13,311
Two miles, and closing.

808
01:35:15,480 --> 01:35:17,755
Stage One alert, please.

809
01:35:17,840 --> 01:35:20,912
Command Centre. All crew to Stage One.

810
01:35:21,000 --> 01:35:22,797
<i>(klaxon)</i>

811
01:35:23,640 --> 01:35:26,108
<i>(guard)</i> Weapons up, second platform.

812
01:35:28,640 --> 01:35:30,790
There he is.

813
01:35:52,360 --> 01:35:55,158
- <i>(guard)</i> Aim.
- <i>(Blofeld)</i> Hold your fire.

814
01:36:09,200 --> 01:36:14,672
<i>(PA) All recovery crew personnel,</i>
<i>proceed to docking level and stand by.</i>

815
01:36:24,560 --> 01:36:27,472
Good morning.
The Acme Pollution Inspection.

816
01:36:27,560 --> 01:36:31,599
We're cleaning up the world and
thought this was a suitable starting point.

817
01:37:01,280 --> 01:37:05,512
How disappointing. I was expecting
one head of state, at the very least.

818
01:37:05,600 --> 01:37:07,636
Surely you haven't come to negotiate?

819
01:37:07,720 --> 01:37:11,713
Your pitiful little island
hasn't even been threatened.

820
01:37:11,800 --> 01:37:16,794
Search him from his toenails to the last
follicle on his head, then bring him to me.

821
01:37:29,680 --> 01:37:33,468
<i>(~ "The British Grenadiers"</i>
<i>played by military band)</i>

822
01:37:40,000 --> 01:37:42,992
I do so hate martial music.

823
01:37:44,480 --> 01:37:47,631
But as usual, Mr Bond,
you were absolutely right.

824
01:37:47,720 --> 01:37:52,157
You guessed correctly, that box contained
the master satellite control tape,

825
01:37:52,240 --> 01:37:58,076
and you came aboard presumably
hoping to substitute this for the real thing.

826
01:38:00,600 --> 01:38:04,513
So sorry to have ruined
the line of your suit for nothing.

827
01:38:06,200 --> 01:38:08,555
Which line did you use on Miss Case?

828
01:38:08,640 --> 01:38:12,076
Miss Case has taken
a reasonable attitude about all this.

829
01:38:12,160 --> 01:38:16,950
Like any sensible animal, she's only
threatening when she's threatened.

830
01:38:17,040 --> 01:38:20,999
It appears that you're holding all the aces,
down to the dragon lady here.

831
01:38:21,080 --> 01:38:25,596
Jealousy? From you, Mr Bond?
I'm flattered.

832
01:38:25,680 --> 01:38:31,357
As La Rochefoucauld observed,
"Humility is the worst form of conceit."

833
01:38:31,440 --> 01:38:33,749
I do hold the winning hand.

834
01:38:33,840 --> 01:38:38,391
Why don't you let me take you
on a little tour of our facilities?

835
01:38:38,480 --> 01:38:42,359
Your chance to see
the real tape once again.

836
01:38:42,440 --> 01:38:45,352
Can I tag along, Ernst?

837
01:38:45,440 --> 01:38:49,274
I'd put something on
over that bikini first, my dear.

838
01:38:49,360 --> 01:38:54,195
I've come too far to have the aim of my
crew affected by the sight of your body.

839
01:38:54,280 --> 01:38:57,431
No word yet from anyone.

840
01:38:57,520 --> 01:38:59,909
Only 12 minutes left.

841
01:39:00,000 --> 01:39:04,357
Oh, well, I suppose
a little gentle prodding is called for.

842
01:39:04,440 --> 01:39:08,672
As you see, Mr Bond,
the satellite is at present over...

843
01:39:09,640 --> 01:39:10,959
Kansas.

844
01:39:12,360 --> 01:39:16,114
But if we destroy Kansas,
the world may not hear about it for years.

845
01:39:16,200 --> 01:39:18,953
Perhaps New York.
All that smut and traffic.

846
01:39:19,040 --> 01:39:21,793
It would give them a chance
for a fresh start.

847
01:39:21,880 --> 01:39:24,155
Washington, DC. Perfect.

848
01:39:24,240 --> 01:39:27,516
Since we have not heard from them,
they will hear from us.

849
01:39:27,600 --> 01:39:31,479
- See to it, Metz.
- Washington. Right.

850
01:39:31,560 --> 01:39:36,076
And this, presumably,
is the control bank with the coded tape.

851
01:39:36,160 --> 01:39:40,711
Right again, Mr Bond. All satellites
are controlled by a coded tape.

852
01:39:40,800 --> 01:39:43,189
The trick is, of course, to have the code.

853
01:39:43,280 --> 01:39:45,748
Obviously.
It all seems so perfectly simple.

854
01:39:45,840 --> 01:39:49,879
I suppose one just presses that
and out it pops.

855
01:39:53,960 --> 01:39:57,396
Put it back, Mr Bond. Immediately.

856
01:40:03,520 --> 01:40:05,317
Hi, Ernst.

857
01:40:05,400 --> 01:40:09,678
- Is Superman giving you any trouble?
- Put it back very carefully.

858
01:40:14,960 --> 01:40:17,394
You've suddenly
become tiresome, Mr Bond.

859
01:40:17,480 --> 01:40:20,153
Target fixed. Commence countdown.

860
01:40:20,240 --> 01:40:22,708
Ten minutes and counting.

861
01:40:22,800 --> 01:40:28,397
Take him away and throw him in the brig.
And search him again, just to make sure.

862
01:40:36,040 --> 01:40:38,156
Bitch.

863
01:40:41,240 --> 01:40:44,277
Your problems are all behind you now.

864
01:41:13,320 --> 01:41:15,311
Stop him!

865
01:41:18,280 --> 01:41:21,033
<i>(PA) Nine minutes and counting.</i>

866
01:41:26,240 --> 01:41:28,834
I did it. I switched the tape in the machine.

867
01:41:28,920 --> 01:41:32,913
- You twit. You put the real one back in.
- Come on, let's go.

868
01:41:53,560 --> 01:41:56,393
<i>(spotter)</i> A weather balloon.

869
01:41:56,840 --> 01:41:59,400
- What do you think?
- That must be the signal.

870
01:41:59,480 --> 01:42:03,951
There isn't a low-pressure area
within 200 miles of here. Let's go.

871
01:42:05,800 --> 01:42:09,395
<i>This is Charlie One to Squadron.</i>
<i>Charlie One to Squadron.</i>

872
01:42:09,480 --> 01:42:14,156
<i>Ready all guns and proceed to target.</i>
<i>I repeat: Proceed to target.</i>

873
01:42:14,240 --> 01:42:16,800
<i>(pilot) Roger, Charlie One. Out.</i>

874
01:42:16,880 --> 01:42:19,952
Come on, Bond.
Get the hell off that rig.

875
01:42:20,040 --> 01:42:22,474
<i>(PA) Eight minutes and counting.</i>

876
01:42:26,200 --> 01:42:30,398
Unidentified aircraft approaching rapidly.
Range five miles.

877
01:42:30,480 --> 01:42:34,632
But I don't understand.
You said they wouldn't attack. You said...

878
01:42:34,720 --> 01:42:39,919
The balloon was a signal. The fools must
think Mr Bond accomplished his mission.

879
01:42:40,000 --> 01:42:42,468
- Activate defences.
- Activate defences.

880
01:42:44,760 --> 01:42:46,751
<i>(klaxon)</i>

881
01:42:54,200 --> 01:42:56,873
<i>Seven minutes and counting.</i>

882
01:43:07,360 --> 01:43:11,069
This is Charlie One. Commence attack.

883
01:43:11,160 --> 01:43:13,674
<i>Commence attack.</i>

884
01:43:44,360 --> 01:43:46,715
Six minutes and counting.

885
01:43:46,800 --> 01:43:49,837
Get them on the radio, Blofeld.
Tell them we give up.

886
01:43:49,920 --> 01:43:53,390
Give up?
I've waited too long for this moment.

887
01:43:53,480 --> 01:43:56,438
They'll pay dearly
for making a fool out of me.

888
01:43:56,520 --> 01:43:59,318
I see it all now.
You don't give a damn about peace.

889
01:43:59,400 --> 01:44:02,198
- All you care about...
- Shut up, Metz.

890
01:44:04,080 --> 01:44:06,594
Tiffany, my dear.

891
01:44:06,680 --> 01:44:10,070
We're showing a bit more cheek
than usual, aren't we?

892
01:44:15,960 --> 01:44:19,430
Take her below and
lock her up with Mr Bond.

893
01:44:19,520 --> 01:44:22,956
What a pity. Such nice cheeks, too.

894
01:44:23,040 --> 01:44:26,715
If only they were brains.
Destroy this, Metz.

895
01:44:41,840 --> 01:44:44,638
<i>Five minutes and counting.</i>

896
01:45:35,760 --> 01:45:38,479
<i>Four minutes and counting.</i>

897
01:45:58,080 --> 01:46:00,753
Tell them we surrender.
This is utter madness.

898
01:46:00,840 --> 01:46:05,311
One more word, Metz, and I'll have you
shot. Get back to your post.

899
01:46:09,000 --> 01:46:11,992
Prepare my bathosub immediately.

900
01:46:20,280 --> 01:46:22,271
<i>Three minutes and counting.</i>

901
01:46:38,480 --> 01:46:40,277
All systems interlock.

902
01:46:40,360 --> 01:46:42,828
<i>Bathosub to crane: Commence lift.</i>

903
01:46:58,400 --> 01:47:00,356
<i>Two minutes and counting.</i>

904
01:47:12,400 --> 01:47:15,949
Power and breathing systems on.
Release catch is open.

905
01:47:18,360 --> 01:47:20,555
Lower away.

906
01:47:21,760 --> 01:47:24,672
<i>Bathosub to crane: Lower away.</i>

907
01:47:26,000 --> 01:47:27,956
Wake up, man. Lower away.

908
01:47:34,760 --> 01:47:37,228
You stupid idiot! You could've killed me.

909
01:47:37,320 --> 01:47:39,151
<i>Disengage.</i>

910
01:47:39,360 --> 01:47:41,157
<i>Disengage.</i>

911
01:47:46,640 --> 01:47:48,039
<i>Disengage!</i>

912
01:47:48,120 --> 01:47:50,793
Lower. Not up.

913
01:47:54,640 --> 01:47:56,870
One minute and counting.

914
01:47:59,040 --> 01:48:03,192
<i>Blofeld to Command Centre: Come in.</i>

915
01:48:03,400 --> 01:48:07,313
<i>Blofeld to Command Centre: Come in.</i>

916
01:48:15,240 --> 01:48:18,630
Damn you! Damn you.
Command Centre, come in.

917
01:48:22,160 --> 01:48:25,072
<i>40 seconds and counting.</i>

918
01:48:31,120 --> 01:48:33,315
Get the gun.

919
01:48:35,880 --> 01:48:37,950
- Here.
- Shoot 'em.

920
01:48:45,640 --> 01:48:47,153
Argh!

921
01:48:52,800 --> 01:48:54,279
Jump!

922
01:48:55,880 --> 01:48:58,075
<i>Ten, nine...</i>

923
01:49:41,920 --> 01:49:45,629
So long, James.
I'll wire M you're on your way home.

924
01:49:45,720 --> 01:49:48,359
Don't tell him which direction we've taken.

925
01:49:48,440 --> 01:49:50,271
If you're havin' a good time,

926
01:49:50,360 --> 01:49:54,831
let the captain know and I'll have him
steam around in circles.

927
01:50:07,040 --> 01:50:13,388
James, there's something very important
I've been meaning to ask you. About us.

928
01:50:14,040 --> 01:50:15,155
Oh?

929
01:50:15,240 --> 01:50:21,236
I know in a relationship like ours, the girl's
not supposed to ask, but I can't help it.

930
01:50:21,320 --> 01:50:25,950
And please think before answering.

931
01:50:26,040 --> 01:50:28,873
- That I promise.
- James...

932
01:50:28,960 --> 01:50:30,439
<i>(knock at door)</i>

933
01:50:42,240 --> 01:50:45,710
There must be some mistake.
I didn't order anything.

934
01:50:45,800 --> 01:50:47,552
No mistake, sir.

935
01:50:47,640 --> 01:50:52,236
On the specific instructions and with
the compliments of Mr Willard Whyte.

936
01:50:52,320 --> 01:50:55,471
Oysters Andaluz.

937
01:50:55,560 --> 01:50:57,198
Shashlik.

938
01:50:57,600 --> 01:51:00,831
Tidbits. Prime rib <i>en jus.</i>

939
01:51:01,840 --> 01:51:03,831
Salade Utopia.

940
01:51:06,960 --> 01:51:11,272
And for dessert, the <i>pièce de résistance,</i>

941
01:51:13,040 --> 01:51:16,032
<i>la bombe surprise.</i>

942
01:51:16,120 --> 01:51:17,917
Hm!

943
01:51:18,000 --> 01:51:21,072
That looks fantastic. What's in it?

944
01:51:21,160 --> 01:51:24,869
But then there would be no <i>surprise,</i>
would there, madame?

945
01:51:24,960 --> 01:51:27,394
- If madam would care to be seated.
- Thank you.

946
01:51:27,480 --> 01:51:31,473
This will just take a moment,
and then we will leave you in peace.

947
01:51:32,480 --> 01:51:36,314
Wine, sir? Mouton Rothschild '55.

948
01:51:37,000 --> 01:51:39,753
- May we begin?
- <i>(Bond)</i> Please do.

949
01:51:43,400 --> 01:51:45,391
<i>(cork pops)</i>

950
01:51:52,200 --> 01:51:56,113
- A happy selection, if I may say.
- I'll be the judge of that.

951
01:51:56,200 --> 01:51:59,795
That's rather potent.
Not the cork - your aftershave.

952
01:51:59,880 --> 01:52:02,599
Strong enough to bury anything.

953
01:52:06,600 --> 01:52:09,239
But the wine is quite excellent.

954
01:52:09,320 --> 01:52:13,313
Although, for such a grand meal,
I had rather expected a claret.

955
01:52:13,400 --> 01:52:18,474
Of course. Unfortunately, our cellar
is rather poorly stocked with clarets.

956
01:52:20,400 --> 01:52:22,595
Mouton Rothschild is a claret.

957
01:52:24,720 --> 01:52:28,429
And I've smelt that aftershave before.
And both times I've smelt a rat.

958
01:52:39,320 --> 01:52:40,309
Yee!

959
01:52:52,200 --> 01:52:54,316
<i>(screams)</i>

960
01:53:13,760 --> 01:53:15,318
Whooh.

961
01:53:15,400 --> 01:53:16,799
Whooooh!

962
01:53:20,480 --> 01:53:21,515
Whoa!

963
01:53:27,240 --> 01:53:31,279
He certainly left
with his tails between his legs.

964
01:53:31,360 --> 01:53:33,635
Oh, James.

965
01:53:33,720 --> 01:53:37,156
Yes, what were you about to ask me?

966
01:53:37,240 --> 01:53:39,071
James...

967
01:53:39,160 --> 01:53:43,153
how the hell do we get
those diamonds down again?

968
01:53:47,320 --> 01:53:50,915
<i>~ Diamonds are forever</i>

969
01:53:51,000 --> 01:53:56,438
<i>~ Sparkling round my little finger</i>

970
01:53:56,520 --> 01:54:00,957
<i>~ Unlike men, the diamonds linger</i>

971
01:54:01,040 --> 01:54:08,515
<i>~ Men are mere mortals</i>
<i>who are not worth going to your grave for</i>

972
01:54:09,920 --> 01:54:14,596
<i>~ I don't need love</i>

973
01:54:14,680 --> 01:54:19,196
<i>~ For what good would love do me?</i>

974
01:54:19,280 --> 01:54:23,432
<i>~ Diamonds never lie to me</i>

975
01:54:24,600 --> 01:54:29,720
<i>~ For when love's gone</i>

976
01:54:29,800 --> 01:54:33,509
<i>~ They'll lustre on</i>

977
01:54:35,560 --> 01:54:40,111
<i>~ Diamonds are forever, forever, forever</i>

978
01:54:40,320 --> 01:54:44,711
<i>~ Diamonds are forever, forever, forever</i>

979
01:54:44,800 --> 01:54:49,271
<i>~ Forever</i>

980
01:54:49,360 --> 01:54:52,909
<i>~ And ever</i>

981
01:54:55,960 --> 01:54:58,952
Visiontext Subtitles: Adrian Isaac

